<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Intermediate Rollers" class="currentChild" href="Intermediate_Rollers">Intermediate Rollers</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
Term for one of two types of rollers found in the <a title="Inking System" href="Inking_System">inking system</a> of a printing press used in <a title="Offset Lithography" href="Offset_Lithography">offset lithography</a>. Intermediates are resilient-surface rollers found adjacent to gear-and-chain-driven, hard-surface rollers (such as <a title="Oscillator" href="Oscillator">oscillator</a>s) and are turned by the force generated on their surfaces by contact with the adjacent rollers. Intermediates (known as <a title="Distributor" href="Distributor">distributor</a>s when falling between two other rollers or as <a title="rider" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/rider">rider</a>s when they contact only one other roller) serve the function of working the ink into the necessary <a title="Viscosity" href="Viscosity">viscosity</a> needed for proper printing, and of mixing the ink with amounts of water to form a proper emulsion. (See <a title="Inking System: Offset Lithography" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/Inking_System:_Offset_Lithography">Inking System: Offset Lithography</a> and <a title="Offset Lithography" href="Offset_Lithography">Offset Lithography</a>.) 
</p>
